If a float establishes a writing mode orthogonal to the one used in the multicol container, only the float's logical width is set. But the amount of logical width taken up by the float in its container is actually the logical *height* of the float, which is 0. So the float is incorrectly believed to take up no space, which causes incorrect position (float:right) or in-flow content overflowing the float (float:left).

Affects both multicol implementations.

The fun starts in RenderBlockFlow::insertFloatingObject():

    bool needsBlockDirectionLocationSetBeforeLayout = isChildRenderBlock &amp;&amp; view()-&gt;layoutState()-&gt;needsBlockDirectionLocationSetBeforeLayout();
    if (!needsBlockDirectionLocationSetBeforeLayout || isWritingModeRoot()) { // We are unsplittable if we're a block flow root.
        floatBox.layoutIfNeeded();
    } else {
        floatBox.updateLogicalWidth();
        floatBox.computeAndSetBlockDirectionMargins(this);
    }

We typically end up in the else-block when inside multicol, which means that we delay laying out the float, which in turn means that we don't get its logical height calculated before we attempt positioning it in positionNewFloats(). While that method does lay out the float, and eventually gets the m_frameRect of the RenderBox right, it fails to set the logical height in FloatingObject::m_frameRect.

TextTrack::setKind can cause a change of the track mode (to 'hidden') if the kind transition from a 'visual' (subtitles/captions) to a 'non-visual' such.

This means that the following two bits of code won't result in the same state, if we start with kind
'captions' and mode 'hidden':

elm.track.kind = 'metadata';
track.mode = 'showing';
// mode is showing

track.mode = 'showing';
elm.track.kind = 'metadata';
// mode is hidden

The spec. does not mention this.

If a block doesn't fit in the current column (or whatever type of fragmentainer), and the block is positioned at the content logical top in its container, it's not pushed to the next column, even if it would fit there. There may be a top margin, border or padding specified on the container, so that the child would fit better in the next column.

Some strut propagation to the container takes place in RenderBlockFlow::adjustBlockChildForPagination() (which seems wrong in this case):

    if (paginationStrut) {
        // We are willing to propagate out to our parent block as long as we were at the top of the block prior
        // to collapsing our margins, and as long as we didn't clear or move as a result of other pagination.
        if (atBeforeSideOfBlock &amp;&amp; oldTop == result &amp;&amp; !isOutOfFlowPositioned() &amp;&amp; !isTableCell()) {
            // FIXME: Should really check if we're exceeding the page height before propagating the strut, but we don't
            // have all the information to do so (the strut only has the remaining amount to push). Gecko gets this wrong too
            // and pushes to the next page anyway, so not too concerned about it.
            setPaginationStrut(result + paginationStrut);
            if (childBlockFlow)
                childBlockFlow-&gt;setPaginationStrut(0);

This is a bug in our generic fragmentation code, and not specific to multicol.

