The PowerSource submessage in powerd's PowerSupplyProperties protocol buffers contains an active_by_default field:

  // True if the power source will automatically deliver charge to the system
  // when connected (assuming there isn't another |active_by_default| source
  // doing so). If false, the source will not deliver charge unless requested
  // to do so by the user.
  optional bool active_by_default = 3;

This was going to be used by Chrome to decide whether to let the user choose which power source to use when multiple potential sources are connected.

Here's powerd's logic for setting the field:

  // Most dedicated chargers will be reported as &quot;Mains&quot;. On spring, low-power
  // USB chargers instead have a &quot;USB&quot;-prefixed type, but they _don't_ have a
  // &quot;status&quot; file (which _is_ present for dual-role USB PD devices).
  const bool active_by_default =
      type == kMainsType || (IsUsbChargerType(type) &amp;&amp; line_status.empty())

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/#/c/249761/ changed the USB PD driver to always use a &quot;USB&quot; type (previously, it used &quot;Mains&quot; for dedicated chargers). This breaks the above powerd code, resulting in it saying that anything connected via USB PD is inactive by default.

I don't think that fixing this is an immediate priority, as I believe that the UI's been punted for now, but it'd be nice to have powerd returning correct information.

Here's Alec's description of the EC logic for determining whether a device should be used as a source:

&quot;the EC tries to speak PD to it
if [it] doesn't speak PD, then we assume it's a dedicated charger
if it does, then one of the bits in the source capabilities packet tells you whether it is a dual-role device or not&quot;

I think that the dual-role-or-not bit needs to be passed up through the kernel so powerd can check it.

